      <abstract abstract-type="teaser">
        <p>SASH3 is an intracellular adaptor protein that is expressed mainly in lymphocytes and is important for proliferation, activation, and survival of T cells. Delmonte and colleagues describe a novel human X-linked immunodeficiency due to hemizygous loss-of-function variants of SASH3. Patients with this immunodeficiency have abnormalities in T cells as well as immune dysregulation manifesting as recurrent infections and refractory autoimmune cytopenias.</p>
      </abstract>
      <abstract abstract-type="executive-summary">
        <title>Key Points</title>
        <p>
<list list-type="bullet"><list-item><p>SASH3 is an adaptor protein expressed mainly in lymphocytes that is important for T-cell proliferation and activation and cell survival.</p></list-item><list-item><p>Hemizygous loss-of-function variants in <italic>SASH3</italic> result in combined immunodeficiency with immune dysregulation.</p></list-item></list>
</p>
      </abstract>
